Bootstrap: docker
From: debian:bookworm-slim

%files
    cpu_thermals /opt/cpu_thermals/cpu_thermals
    pyproject.toml /opt/cpu_thermals/pyproject.toml
    README.md /opt/cpu_thermals/README.md

%post
    apt-get update && apt-get install -y --no-install-recommends python3 python3-pip lm-sensors
    cd /opt/cpu_thermals
    # --break-system-packages because Alpines Python is marked PEP 668
    # externally-managed; this is the standard pattern for installing a
    # single first-party package into a container.
    python3 -m pip install --no-cache-dir --break-system-packages .
    # Drop the source tree to slim the image; the installed package is
    # already in site-packages and the entry point is on PATH.
    rm -rf /opt/cpu_thermals

%environment
    export PATH=/usr/local/bin:/usr/bin:$PATH

%runscript
    exec cpu-thermals "$@"

%labels
    Author cnh
    Project cpu_thermals
    Version 0.1.0
    Description Live CPU temperature monitor (Linux backend via lm-sensors)

%help
    Live CPU temperature monitor packaged for Apptainer.

    Build:  ./build.sh
    Run:    ./run.sh                  # default 2-second TUI table
            ./run.sh 0.5              # twice-per-second refresh
            ./run.sh --csv ~/cpu.csv  # also record CSV to a host-visible path
            ./run.sh --csv -          # stream CSV to stdout (TUI auto-suppressed)

    What this image carries:
        python3, the cpu_thermals package, and the lm-sensors userspace
        binary + libsensors. No userspace tooling needs to be installed
        on the host -- everything cpu-thermals talks to is in here.

    What the host must provide:
        1. A Linux kernel (any recent version; hwmon has been in-tree
           since 2.6.x).
        2. The right hwmon driver module loaded for your CPU. On modern
           distros this is automatic via udev:
               Intel  -> coretemp
               AMD    -> k10temp
           If you don't see /sys/class/hwmon/hwmon*/name reporting one
           of these, load the module manually as root:
               sudo modprobe coretemp     # or k10temp on AMD
        3. Apptainer 1.x (or legacy Singularity 3.x) on PATH.

    Verify the host is ready (no install required):
        ls /sys/class/hwmon/
        cat /sys/class/hwmon/hwmon*/name      # must include coretemp or k10temp

    Apptainer auto-mounts /sys, $HOME, $PWD, and /tmp from the host, so
    sensor reads and CSV writes Just Work without explicit --bind flags.
